f there is none, return 0.\nAn axis-aligned plus sign of 1's of order k has some center grid[r][c] == 1 along with four arms of length k - 1 going up, down, left, and right, and made of 1's. Note that there could be 0's or 1's beyond the arms of the plus sign, only the relevant area of the plus sign is checked for 1's.\n \nExample 1:\n\n\nInput: n = 5, mines = [[4,2]]\nOutput: 2\nExplanation: In the above grid, the largest plus sign can only be of order 2. One of them is shown.\n\nExample 2:\n\n\nInput: n = 1, mines = [[0,0]]\nOutput: 0\nExplanation: There is no plus sign, so return 0.\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n1 <= n <= 500\n1 <= mines.length <= 5000\n0 <= xi, yi < n\nAll the pairs (xi, yi) are unique.\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def orderOfLargestPlusSign(self, n: int, mines: List[List[int]]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def orderOfLargestPlusSign(self, n: int, mines: List[List[int]]) -> int:\n        # Create a set of mines for O(1) look-up time\n        mines_set = set(tuple(mine) for mine in mines)\n        \n        # Initialize the dp array\n        dp = [[[0, 0, 0, 0] for _ in range(n)] for _ in range(n)]\n        \n        # Fill the dp array for left and top directions\n        for i in range(n):\n            for j in range(n):\n                if (i, j) not in mines_set:\n                    top = dp[i-1][j][0] if i > 0 else 0\n                    left = dp[i][j-1][3] if j > 0 else 0\n                    dp[i][j][0] = top + 1\n                    dp[i][j][3] = left + 1\n        \n        # Fill the dp array for right and bottom directions and calculate the result\n        order = 0\n        for i in range(n-1, -1, -1):\n            for j in range(n-1, -1, -1):\n                if (i, j) not in mines_set:\n                    bottom = dp[i+1][j][2] if i < n-1 else 0\n                    right = dp[i][j+1][1] if j < n-1 else 0\n                    dp[i][j][2] = bottom + 1\n                    dp[i][j][1] = right + 1\n                    # The order of the plus sign is the minimum of the four directions\n                    order = max(order, min(dp[i][j]))\n        \n        return order\n```\n\nThis solution initializes a 3D DP array where each cell contains four values representing the lengths of consecutive 1's in the top, right, bottom, and left directions from that cell. It first fills the DP array for the top and left directions, and then for the bottom and right directions while updating the maximum order of the plus sign found. The time complexity is O(n^2), which is efficient given the constraints.", "estimated_date": 1438905600000}